Fantasy Baseball Head-to-Head Models - SVM¶

Introduction¶

This project explores weekly matchup data from my fantasy baseball league for the 2011-2019 seasons.
Parts of this analysis are motivated by Peadar Coyle's Rugby Analysis case study, and PyMC3's GLM: Logistic Regression example.

The data was collected using the Yahoo Fantasy Baseball API and is available in a local PostgreSQL database.

The league consists of 14 teams and each season usually consists of 21 weekly matchups.
Scoring is based on 18 statistical categories. Weekly "scores" are based on the head-to-head matchup in each category. Category wins, losses and ties are compiled each week and throughout the season to determine the league standings.

The 2016-2019 seasons were chosen because the categories were consistent throughout those four seasons.
They consist of the following counting (aggregate) categories as identified in the data:

Batting: b_BB: Walks; b_HR: Home Runs; b_K: Strikeouts; b_NSB: Net Stolen Bases; b_R: Runs; b_RBI: Runs Batted In.
Pitching: p_BB: Walks; p_IP: Innings Pitched; p_K: Strikeouts; p_L: Losses; p_NSVH: Net Saves and Holds; p_QS: Quality Starts; p_W: Wins.

The rest are rate categories:

Batting: b_AVGr: Batting Average; b_OBPr: On-Base Percentage; b_SLGr: Slugging Percentage.
Pitching: p_ERAr: Earned-run Average; p_WHIPr: Walks plus Hits per Innings Pitched.

As noted above, the season standings are not influenced by the overall weekly winner, and consist of an aggregate score. For example, in a weekly matchup of two teams, the result is not purely a win or a loss. The "winning" team might win 10 categories, lose six and tie two, and the "score" of 10-6-2 is simply added to their standings.

Despite this, Yahoo's API includes a "weekly winning team" category, and for the sake of exploring the data and Bayesian approaches, the concept of a team winning the weekly matchup will be used to develop exploratory models.

def train_model(df, category, C_gamma=None):
    
    '''
    df: data used to fit model
    category: category to model
    C_gamma: Optional 'C' and 'gamma' values for the svm model
        The train_svc function will choose the optimal parameters, but enter values here to test further
    '''
    
    # filter dataset by category
    category_mask = df['category'] == category

    # stack and unstack
    df = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[category_mask, ['matchup', 'value', 'won_week', 'matchup_id']].groupby(['matchup', 'matchup_id'])['value', 'won_week'].sum()).unstack()

    print(f'\nStacked and filtered dataset:\n {df}\n')

    X = df[['value']].values
    y = df[['won_week']].values[:, 0]
    
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=42)
    sns.scatterplot(x = X_train[:, 0], y = X_train[:, 1], hue = y_train)
    
    def prediction(fitted_model, Xtest, ytest):
        y_pred = fitted_model.predict(Xtest)

        print(f'\nScore:\n{fitted_model.score(Xtest, ytest)}\n')

        print(f'\nConfusion matrix:\n{confusion_matrix(ytest,y_pred)}\n')

    def train_svc(Xtrain, ytrain):
        
        # Scale -> Update this with other project.ipynb scaling

        # It is usually a good idea to scale the data for SVM training.
        # We are cheating a bit in this example in scaling all of the data,
        # instead of fitting the transformation on the training set and
        # just applying it on the test set.

        # scaler = StandardScaler()
        # X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)

        # Train classifiers
        #
        # For an initial search, a logarithmic grid with basis
        # 10 is often helpful. Using a basis of 2, a finer
        # tuning can be achieved but at a much higher cost.
        C_range = np.logspace(-2, 4, 7)
        gamma_range = np.logspace(-9, 2, 12)
        param_grid = dict(gamma = gamma_range, C=C_range)
        cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=6, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
        grid_cv = GridSearchCV(svm.SVC(), param_grid=param_grid, cv=cv, verbose=1)
        grid_cv.fit(Xtrain, ytrain)

        print("The best parameters are %s with a score of %0.2f"
              % (grid_cv.best_params_, grid_cv.best_score_))

        return grid_cv

    def plot_svc(model, Xtrain, ytrain):
        
        print(f'\nModel:\n{model}\n')

        model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain)

        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

        plt.scatter(Xtrain[:, 0], Xtrain[:, 1], c=ytrain, s=30, cmap=plt.cm.Paired)
        ax = plt.gca()
        xlim = ax.get_xlim()
        ylim = ax.get_ylim()

        # create grid to evaluate model
        xx = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 30)
        yy = np.linspace(ylim[0], ylim[1], 30)
        YY, XX = np.meshgrid(yy, xx)
        xy = np.vstack([XX.ravel(), YY.ravel()]).T
        Z = model.decision_function(xy).reshape(XX.shape)

        # plot decision boundary and margins
        ax.contour(XX, YY, Z, colors='k', levels=[-1, 0, 1], alpha=0.5,
                   linestyles=['--', '-', '--'])
        # plot support vectors
        ax.scatter(model.support_vectors_[:, 0], model.support_vectors_[:, 1], s=100,
                   linewidth=1, facecolors='none', edgecolors='k')
        plt.show()

        return model

    if C_gamma is None:
        grid = train_svc(X_train, y_train)
        clf = plot_svc(svm.SVC(C=grid.best_params_['C'], gamma=grid.best_params_['gamma']), X_train, y_train)
        print(prediction(clf, X_test, y_test))        
        return clf
    else:
        for i, cg in enumerate(C_gamma.items()):
            print(f'\nC: {cg[0][i]}\n')
            print(f'\ngamma: {cg[1][i]}\n')
            grid = train_svc(X_train, y_train)
            clf = plot_svc(svm.SVC(C=C_gamma['C'][i], gamma=C_gamma['gamma'][i]), X_train, y_train)
            print(prediction(clf, X_test, y_test))
            if len(C_gamma['C']) == 1:
                return clf
In [5]:
def test_model(df, category, model):
    
    '''
    df: data used to test model
    category: category to model
    model: existing model
    '''

    # filter dataset by category
    category_mask = df['category'] == category

    # stack and unstack
    df = pd.DataFrame(df.loc[category_mask, ['matchup', 'value', 'won_week', 'matchup_id']].groupby(['matchup', 'matchup_id'])['value', 'won_week'].sum()).unstack()

    print(f'\nStacked and filtered dataset:\n {df}\n')

    X = df[['value']].values
    y = df[['won_week']].values[:, 0]
    
    y_pred = model.predict(X)

    print(f'\nScore:\n{model.score(X, y)}\n')

    print(f'\nConfusion matrix:\n{confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)}\n')
